g.text: Any irrational number {\displaystyle r}r that is greater than one generates the Beatty sequence
The two irrational numbers {\displaystyle r}r and {\displaystyle s=r/(r-1)}{\displaystyle s=r/(r-1)}
naturally satisfy the equation {\displaystyle 1/r+1/s=1}1/r+1/s=1. The two Beatty sequences
that they generate form a pair of complementary Beatty sequences. Here,
"complementary" means that every positive integer belongs to exactly one of these two sequences.
